\par\pard\plain \sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs32\b1 3}{\f0\fs24  (18:2\endash 8) }{\f0\fs24\b1 Service\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 Ministry}{\f0\fs24  How can we become a friend of God? Serve and meet the needs of people. Abraham is a strong example in serving others, and remember he was one of the most powerful sheiks in Canaan, if not the most powerful (Ge. 14:1\endash 24).}
\par\pard\plain \fi360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 a. Abraham, sitting there in the doorway of his tent, looked up; and immediately he saw three men standing nearby (v. 2). Who were the three men? The }{\f0\fs24\scaps Lord}{\f0\fs24  and two angels. Several verses tell us this (v. 1, 10, 13, 14). When did Abraham know that it was the }{\f0\fs24\scaps Lord}{\f0\fs24 ? We cannot tell from the story, but he certainly knew by verse ten when the }{\f0\fs24\scaps Lord}{\f0\fs24  reconfirmed the promise of the promised seed or son. It is, of course, possible\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 perhaps probable\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 that the }{\f0\fs24\scaps Lord}{\f0\fs24  revealed Himself from the first. We certainly do not have the whole conversation here, and it would seem reasonable to expect the }{\f0\fs24\scaps Lord}{\f0\fs24  to reveal His identity.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 b. Abraham ran to meet the men (v. 2). He did not have to do this: he could have ignored them, just let them pass by, or sent one of his servants out to them. After all, he was resting and praying and thinking through the enormous life-changing plans God had thrust upon him. But Abraham cared about people: he knew the travelers were walking out in the noon day heat and had most likely been traveling all morning. He knew they would be tired, thirsty, hungry, and dirty. He could not fail to offer them help and refreshment.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 c. Abraham bowed, was humble and courteous (v. 2). Again, remember his status was that of a powerful sheik, yet he went out to them himself, demonstrating a most courteous, humble posture: he bowed to the ground. Bowing to the ground may indicate that Abraham knew that it was the }{\f0\fs24\scaps Lord}{\f0\fs24  and angels from the first.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 d. Abraham sought to help and spend time with the three men (vv. 3\endash 5). He showed the most gracious hospitality, inviting them to come to his home so that he could minister to their needs. He offered them water to drink and to wash their dusty feet. He also offered them food and the opportunity to rest. Note that they accepted the invitation.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 e. Abraham involved his wife in serving (v. 6). He did not act alone. Serving others is both a privilege and a duty. He wanted the person most dear to him by his side, serving right along with him as he ministered. He wanted Sarah to fulfill her duty as the wife and to experience the joy of the occasion herself.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 f. Abraham gave the best he had (v. 7). He ran to his herd, selected, and prepared a young calf to serve\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 a choice, tender calf.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 g. Abraham served the men himself: he became personally involved (v. 8). He could have sat down with them and had Sarah or servants serve them all together. But Abraham took the posture of a servant and served the three men himself. He became personally involved in the service and ministry: he sought to personally meet their needs.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24 h. Abraham demonstrated humility: he stood off to the side just as a servant would. He did not sit down with them. (This would indicate that Abraham knew that he was serving the }{\f0\fs24\scaps Lord}{\f0\fs24  Himself. Being a powerful sheik, he most likely would have sat and had conversation with other men.)}
\par\pard\plain \li720\sb180\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b1 Thought 1}{\f0\fs24 . Abraham is a dynamic example in serving others. He was a humble, ministry-minded person. Remember how he offered Lot the first choice of land (Ge. 13:8\endash 9); how he rescued the people of Canaan, including Lot, from the invading army; how he accepted Hagar back after she had run away with their son, Ishmael (Ge. 16:1\endash 16).}
\par\pard\plain \li720\fi360\qj\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 Abraham was always serving and helping others. And he was, no doubt, very busy managing his large holdings. Again, he is a strong example for us in serving others. We should always be looking to help people in need. When we spot people in need, we should run to meet them, be courteous, and seek to help meet their needs. We should follow the very steps that Abraham took in meeting the needs of these three men.\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  Leadership Ministries Worldwide. (1996). \\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosres/posbkjv01ge2?ref=Bible.Ge18.2-8&off=0&ctx=heart%E2%80%9D+(Je.+29:13).%0a~3+(18:2%E2%80%938)+Service%E2%80%94M"}{\fldrslt\f2\fs24\b0\i1\ul\ulc0\cf3 Genesis (Chapters 12\endash 50)\\end_Scrv_fn\}\{\\Scrv_fn=}}{\f1\fs24\b0\i0  (Vol. II, p. 90). Chattanooga, TN: Leadership Ministries Worldwide.\\end_Scrv_fn\}}
